### What the Analysis Revealed

**Finding 1: The price-to-income ratio has never been this high and is not coming down.**

In 1984 the median home cost roughly 1.5 to 2 times median annual household income, comfortably below the 3x rule of thumb. That ratio climbed through the 1990s, peaked during the mid-2000s bubble at around 5x, partially corrected after the financial crisis, and then surged to nearly 8x in 2021. As of 2024 it sits at approximately 7x — more than double the traditional benchmark and more than three times where it was forty years ago. Higher interest rates have cooled price growth but have not meaningfully reduced the ratio.

**Finding 2: The payment-to-income ratio tells a more nuanced story about two different kinds of affordability crisis.**

The early 1980s were actually the most payment-unaffordable period in the entire dataset — not because prices were high, but because 30-year mortgage rates were above 13 percent. Monthly payments consumed nearly 48 percent of median monthly income in 1984. Affordability then improved dramatically through the 1990s and 2000s as rates fell, even while prices rose, because cheaper financing kept monthly payments manageable. By 2021, with rates near historic lows, monthly payments had fallen back to around 25 to 27 percent of income despite record home prices.

The 2022 rate shock reversed all of that. The Federal Reserve's hiking cycle pushed 30-year rates from below 3 percent to nearly 8 percent in under two years. Monthly payments as a share of income shot back up to approximately 47 to 48 percent at the peak. As of 2024, with rates around 6.5 to 7 percent, the payment burden sits at roughly 44 percent of monthly income — well above the 28 percent threshold and with no clear path back down.

**Finding 3: The indexed series shows the full structural divergence.**

When all three variables are indexed to 1984 equal 100, the gap becomes immediately visible. Home prices have grown roughly 620 percent above their 1984 level. Real median income has grown only about 57 percent over the same period. Falling mortgage rates from the mid-1980s through 2021 partially masked this divergence by keeping monthly payments affordable even as prices rose. Once that tailwind reversed in 2022, there was no buffer left.

**The key insight is that the current crisis is different from the early 1980s.** In 1984, the problem was high rates on an affordable price base — fix the rates and affordability recovers. Today, both prices and rates are elevated simultaneously. Even if rates fall back to 5 percent, the price-to-income ratio would still be around 6x to 7x, which is historically extreme. There is no easy fix.

### Methodology Notes

- **Price-to-income ratio:** median home price divided by real median annual household income
- **Payment-to-income ratio:** standard amortization formula, 20% down, 30-year fixed, expressed as share of median monthly income
- **Indexed series:** each variable divided by its Q1 1984 value multiplied by 100
- **Income frequency:** annual income forward-filled to quarterly; testing interpolation as an alternative is still on the to-do list

### Limitations

All three series are national aggregates so regional variation is invisible. MSPUS covers new construction only. The 20 percent down payment assumption does not reflect first-time buyer reality. Renter affordability is not captured.

### Next Steps

The national picture is now well-established. The next phase will focus on whether to bring in metro-level data from Zillow or the Census ACS to examine whether the post-2020 affordability collapse was uniform across cities or whether some markets recovered faster than others.

